<p>&#8230;</p>
<p>There are so many things wrong with this post it isn't even funny.</p>
<p>The main thing being that for the majority of Christians, Genesis 1-15 (that would be including Cain and Abel) is completely fictional anyway. It's a <em>myth</em>, written as a counter to other common myths of the day, most specifically the <em>Enuma Elish</em> and the <em>Epic of Gilgamesh</em>. What's important is the <em>meaning</em>, not the contents of the story itself, because it's not <em>meant</em> to be taken as historical fact. Cain and Able's articles hinge on the idea of &quot;what if it was historical fact and got it wrong&quot; which is fine and good, but please remember:</p>
<p><strong>THIS IS FICTION. IT IS A FICTIONAL SHORT STORY ON THE INTERNET, MEANT FOR ENTERTAINMENT, NOT FOR THE IMPARTING OF MORAL LESSONS. IT IS NOT A RELIABLE REPLACEMENT FOR THEOLOGICAL, PHILOSOPHICAL, LITERARY OR HISTORICAL STUDY OF FICTIONAL STORIES MEANT TO IMPART MORAL LESSONS OR HISTORICAL ACCOUNTS OF THE SAME PURPOSE.</strong></p>
